{
  "answer": "Iqbal's poem \"Insaan\" (\"The Human Being\") in *Bang-E-Dara Part 3* presents humanity in stark contrast to the passive natural world: all other things are \"accustomed to submission,\" but the human's every power \"is aflame with striving.\"[^1] The human is no mere \"particle\" but a vast potentiality—a \"desert contracted to a point\"—yearning for boundlessness, wise, perceptive, and potent enough to reshape reality itself.[^2] Iqbal thus privileges **individual dynamism and creative agency**, elevating the human as an active force of self-overcoming and transformation, unbound by static nature or fate.\n\nManu's *Manusmṛti* Chapter 1, by contrast, embeds the human within a cosmic order of creation, where the primordial being divides humanity into four *varnas* (social classes)—Brahmana from the mouth, Kshatriya from the arms, Vaishya from the thighs, and Shudra from the feet—for the \"prosperity of the worlds,\" each with rigidly assigned duties.[^3] Humans are hierarchically ordered by purity and function (purer \"above the navel,\" with the mouth supreme), intelligence, and role: Brahmanas for sacred learning and rites, Kshatriyas for protection, Vaishyas for economic sustenance, Shudras for service.[^4] Manu privileges **social hierarchy and varna-dharma** (class-based righteousness), defining the human above all by inherited position, duty, and collective cosmic stability rather than individual striving.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/12-insaan/translation/#p-cb3c43).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/12-insaan/translation/#p-2697a9-p-587d8c).\n[^3]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-13a2db).\n[^4]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-4809ee-p-fdb716-p-71a5c2-p-a09d4d-p-357321-p-26a572).",
